abstract: TO CURE HAMS. Take the hams as soon as cut, lay on a dry shelf, take one tablespoonful of saltpetre to a ham and rub, thoroughly on the fleshy side of the ham; as soon as dissolved the next day rub all over with dry salt, in the bone and every crevice; after rubbing two or three times, they are ready for smoking; cover well, and hang up to dry. C. T.

abstract: HARRISBURG, Penn., Sept. 12. A convention of the Prohibition Party of Pennsylvania was held in this city to-day. Not more than 30 delegates were present, representing less than a dozen counties, and the proceedings were tame and uninteresting. The convention set a good example to other assemblages of like character and purpose by opening their proceedings with prayer.

abstract: The steam-ship Juana, which arrived at this port on Sunday last from Havana, with six cases of yellow fever on board, is still lying at Lower Quarantine, and the patients are under treatment at the yellow fever hospital. abstract: The case of Patrick Roden, who was arraigned a Jefferson Market Police Court, yesterday, charged with assaulting his wife with intent to kill her, revealed a very sad state of domestie affairs. Roden is a tailor, aged 48, and well-to-do. He lives at No. 302 West Sixteenth-street., occupying several rooms on the third floor.

abstract: Mr. J.Q. Hoyt, the Trustee of the Clairmont Savings Bank to whom its ruin appears to be due, was made highly indignant yesterday morning by the reports which he read in the papers of his transactions with the institution. abstract: ROME, N.Y., Sept. 21. The westward-bound Chicago express train, which was due in Rome at 5:15 P.M., was thrown into collision with a pick-up freight train by a misplaced switch, one mile east of Rome depot. Both engines were completely wrecked, and the mail and baggage cars were ground together in an almost solid mass.

abstract: Albert Lavergne, the Frenchman who shot himself in the left breast at No. 101 West Fourteenth-street on Wednesday night, was lying at the New-York Hospital last night, and, according to the physicians there, is not in any immediate danger.
